{"id":1227,"date":"2013-07-05T12:25:02","date_gmt":"2013-07-05T12:25:02","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/joind.co.uk\/?p=1227"},"modified":"2017-02-12T16:17:43","modified_gmt":"2017-02-12T16:17:43","slug":"library-birmingham-open-closed","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/library-birmingham-open-closed\/","title":{"rendered":"Library of Birmingham: Opening what was closed"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>When the \u00a3188.8 million <a href=\"http:\/\/www.libraryofbirmingham.com\/\" target=\"_blank\">Library of Birmingham<\/a> opens to the public, \u00a0it will be more than the doors that are swung wide. \u00a0The library will be open in ways it has never been before.<!--more--><\/p>\n<p>Take the storage areas as an example. \u00a0In every library there are archive areas that the public can not enter, but in the Library of Birmingham, every effort is being made to open up the hidden spaces. Archives are being put online. Collections will be displayed in the galleries. In future, we are far more likely to know about the treasures that our library has in store.<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_1571\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-1571\" style=\"width: 450px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><a href=\"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/Library-of-Birmingham-opening-what-was-closed-by-Jo-Ind.jpg\" rel=\"lightbox[1227]\"><img fetchpriority=\"high\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-1571\" src=\"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/Library-of-Birmingham-opening-what-was-closed-by-Jo-Ind-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"View of the skylight in the Library of Birmingham\" width=\"450\" height=\"338\" srcset=\"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/Library-of-Birmingham-opening-what-was-closed-by-Jo-Ind-300x225.jpg 300w, https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/Library-of-Birmingham-opening-what-was-closed-by-Jo-Ind-973x730.jpg 973w, https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/Library-of-Birmingham-opening-what-was-closed-by-Jo-Ind-508x381.jpg 508w, https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/Library-of-Birmingham-opening-what-was-closed-by-Jo-Ind.jpg 1000w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 450px) 100vw, 450px\" \/><\/a><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-1571\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Looking up to the sky from the foyer of the Library of Birmingham<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>The library opens us up to the city too. When we arrive in the extensive foyer, we have a view of Centenary Square at the front, Cambridge Street at the back, and even the sky.\u00a0With a few exceptions &#8211; like the loos &#8211; wherever we go in the building, \u00a0we get to see Birmingham in new ways.<\/p>\n<p>Even where the library goes underground (that&#8217;s where the Music Library and Children&#8217;s Library are), we end up at an amphitheatre, a great window in Centenary Square that means anyone passing can look down and see inside the library and anyone inside the library can look up and see the sky.<\/p>\n<p>As for the staff &#8211; they won&#8217;t be able to pick their noses at they sit at their desks. \u00a0Their offices have glass walls so people using the library will be able to see them at work. Quite how they feel about this remains to be seen&#8230;<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_2799\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-2799\" style=\"width: 450px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><a href=\"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/02\/Ironwork-from-inside-the-Library-of-Birmingham-Christian-Richters.jpg\" rel=\"lightbox[1227]\"><img decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-2799\" src=\"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/02\/Ironwork-from-inside-the-Library-of-Birmingham-Christian-Richters.jpg\" width=\"450\" height=\"338\" srcset=\"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/02\/Ironwork-from-inside-the-Library-of-Birmingham-Christian-Richters.jpg 800w, https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/02\/Ironwork-from-inside-the-Library-of-Birmingham-Christian-Richters-300x225.jpg 300w, https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/02\/Ironwork-from-inside-the-Library-of-Birmingham-Christian-Richters-768x576.jpg 768w, https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/02\/Ironwork-from-inside-the-Library-of-Birmingham-Christian-Richters-700x525.jpg 700w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 450px) 100vw, 450px\" \/><\/a><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-2799\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Looking out over the city &#8211; Christian Richters<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>I love it. I love it because it says to me that growing, learning and discovering are not things we do just on our own (there is always an element of that, of course) but what we do together. Simply being in the library engenders in me a sense of pride, hope and belonging.<\/p>\n<p>On Tuesday 3 September 2013, we will be able to proudly announce that the Library of Birmingham is open &#8211; and that is a far more radical statement than it seems.<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>\u00a0<strong>I am a\u00a0<a href=\"http:\/\/www.libraryofbirmingham.com\/lobfaces\" target=\"_blank\">Face of the Library of Birmingham<\/a>\u00a0and one of its Ambassadors. This post is the second in a <a title=\"Library of Birmingham: The day I went inside\" href=\"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/library-birmingham-day-went-inside\/\" target=\"_blank\">series of four<\/a> written after going inside the building for the first time in July 2013.<\/strong><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>When the \u00a3188.8 million Library of Birmingham opens to the public, \u00a0it will be more than the doors that are swung wide. \u00a0The library will be open in ways it has never been before.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":2799,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"footnotes":""},"categories":[3],"tags":[120],"class_list":["post-1227","post","type-post","status-publ